a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes f g :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall>x. f x = x + 3"
and h1 : "\<forall>x. g x = 3 * x + 5"
shows  "f (g 4) - g (f 4) = -6"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Let $f(x)=x+3$ and $g(x)=3x+5$.  Find $f(g(4))-g(f(4))$. The final Answer is -6
 ### Proof
 We have $g(4) = 3\cdot 4 + 5= 17$, so $f(g(4)) = f(17) = 17 + 3 = 20$.
 We also have $f(4) = 4+3 = 7$, so $g(f(4)) = g(7)=3\cdot 7 + 5 = 26$.
 Therefore, $f(g(4)) - g(f(4)) = 20 - 26 = \boxed{-6}$.
 *)

theorem
fixes f g :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall>x. f x = x + 3"
and h1 : "\<forall>x. g x = 3 * x + 5"
shows  "f (g 4) - g (f 4) = -6"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: Given the functions $f(x) = x + 3$ and $g(x) = 3x + 5$, find the value of $f(g(4)) - g(f(4))$. The final answer is $-6$.
